Zendesk provides an official, early-access program (EAP) to connect Zendesk to external MCP servers directly through its Admin Center for use in action flows [1]. This native integration supports HTTP servers with OAuth 2.0 authentication [1].

Alternatively, multiple open-source MCP servers exist for connecting local AI clients (such as Claude Desktop, Cursor, or VS Code) to Zendesk [2][3][4][5][6][7][8]. These servers use various authentication methods, including API tokens [2][6][7][8] or OAuth 2.1 PKCE [5]. Popular options include:

- @fruggr/zendesk-mcp-server: Focuses on OAuth-only security and two-way Help Center/Support integration [5].
- mattcoatsworth/zendesk-mcp-server: A feature-complete implementation for tickets, users, macros, and more [2].
- zendesk-mcp (Sajiiidddd): Provides over 60 tools for extensive Zendesk control [6].

To use these community servers, configure your MCP client's settings file with the appropriate environment variables [6][7][8]. Example for Claude Desktop:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "zendesk": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "zd-mcp-server"],
      "env": {
        "ZENDESK_SUBDOMAIN": "your-subdomain",
        "ZENDESK_EMAIL": "you@example.com",
        "ZENDESK_TOKEN": "your-api-token"
      }
    }
  }
}
```
